snippet.textDisplay:
A Seattle developer took declining malls towards being the Third Place of community gathering;  locations where ideas exchange, people relax, and build relationships. We have home and work but need a public place to get together socially between home and work
Seattle's Third Place malls offer the anchoring Third Place Bookstores with author talks and small local music performances besides new and used books The greater space is a comfortable array of tables & chairs for people to meet, read, chat or work in a food court focused on the public gathering rather than food sales volume. The center can be cleared for dance lessons or other larger events open to the public. There are rooms the public can reserve for club meetings or demos that would disturb the larger public space. The rest of the mall is retail shopping and professional services.
